<TEXT ID="962">
<TITLE>Neidhart von Reuental</TITLE>

<PARAGRAPH>
<REF MENTION="1" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="plain" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Neidhart von Reuental</REFEX></REF>
 (MHG: Nîthart von Riuwental) was one of the most famous German minnesingers. 
<REF MENTION="2" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 was born in Bavaria and 
<REF MENTION="3" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="no_case" REG08-TYPE="empty" ENTITY="0">_</REFEX></REF>
 lived in Austria. As a minnesinger 
<REF MENTION="4" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 was most active from 1210 to 1240. 
<REF MENTION="5" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 is very well known for being rather sarcastic and comical. More melodies survive by 
<REF MENTION="6" SYNFUNC="obj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="plain" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Neidhart</REFEX></REF>
 than from any other minnesinger.
</PARAGRAPH>

<PARAGRAPH>
<REF MENTION="7" SYNFUNC="subj-det" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="genitive" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Neidhart's</REFEX></REF>
 name is most likely a pseudonym, for its meaning is more or less Grim-Heart of Lament-Valley. The second part of 
<REF MENTION="8" SYNFUNC="subj-det" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="genitive" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">his</REFEX></REF>
 name, however, was "reconstructed" by philologists of the 19th century, who took literally the role of the "speaker," who calls himself "von Reuental" in 
<REF MENTION="9" SYNFUNC="subj-det" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="genitive" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">his</REFEX></REF>
 poems, and thus combined it with 
<REF MENTION="10" SYNFUNC="subj-det" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="genitive" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">his</REFEX></REF>
 name, which was simply "Nithart". All manuscript sources until the 15th century refer to 
<REF MENTION="11" SYNFUNC="obj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="accusative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">him</REFEX></REF>
 only as "Nithart". 
<REF MENTION="12" SYNFUNC="subj-det" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="genitive" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Neidhart's</REFEX></REF>
 songs often stand in harsh contrast to the normal minnesinger topic, courtly or romantic love. This style has been referred to as Höfische Dorfpoesie (courtly village-poetry) by 
<REF MENTION="1" SYNFUNC="obj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="1"><REFEX CASE="plain" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="1">philologist Karl Lachmann</REFEX></REF>
 and was often imitated by composers called pseudo-Neidharts.
</PARAGRAPH>

<PARAGRAPH>
Probably 
<REF MENTION="13" SYNFUNC="subj-det" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="genitive" REG08-TYPE="name" ENTITY="0">Neidhart's</REFEX></REF>
 best-known song is Meienzît (May Time) in which 
<REF MENTION="14" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 starts with describing a peaceful spring scenario but 
<REF MENTION="15" SYNFUNC="subj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="nominative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">he</REFEX></REF>
 quickly comes to insulting 
<REF MENTION="16" SYNFUNC="subj-det" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="genitive" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">his</REFEX></REF>
 foes (and several friends and allies that betrayed 
<REF MENTION="17" SYNFUNC="obj" SYNCAT="np" SEMCAT="person" ENTITY="0"><REFEX CASE="accusative" REG08-TYPE="pronoun" ENTITY="0">him</REFEX></REF>
).
</PARAGRAPH>
